%N A397173 Irregular triangle T(n,k) (n >= 2, k>=0) read by rows: T(n,k) = number of times the sum W(i)+W(j) is equal to k, for 1 <= i < j <= n, where W is Weinstein's sequence A394611.
%C A397173 The rows converge to A397174.
%C A397173 Row n accounts for all previous rows and n-1 new sums W(k) + W(n), 1<=k<n, hence the sum of the terms in row n is A000217(n-1).
%e A397173 Triangle begins as follow (the first row is row 2):
%e A397173   [1],
%e A397173   [1, 2],
%e A397173   [1, 2, 2, 1],
%e A397173   [1, 2, 4, 2, 1],
%e A397173   [1, 2, 4, 2, 3, 1, 2],
%e A397173   [1, 2, 4, 4, 4, 3, 2, 1],
%e A397173   [1, 2, 4, 4, 6, 4, 4, 2, 1],
%e A397173   [1, 2, 4, 4, 6, 4, 6, 3, 3, 1, 2],
%e A397173   [1, 2, 4, 4, 6, 4, 8, 4, 5, 2, 4, 0, 1],
%e A397173   [1, 2, 4, 4, 6, 4, 8, 4, 7, 3, 6, 1, 3, 0, 2],
%e A397173   [1, 2, 4, 4, 6, 4, 8, 6, 8, 5, 7, 3, 3, 2, 2, 1],
%e A397173   [1, 2, 4, 4, 6, 4, 10, 7, 10, 6, 9, 3, 5, 3, 3, 1],
%e A397173   [1, 2, 4, 4, 6, 4, 10, 7, 10, 6, 11, 4, 7, 4, 5, 1, 3, 1, 1],
%e A397173 ...
%e A397173 For row 2, we have W(1)+W(2) = 0+0 = 0, so the sum 0 has occurred 1 time. No other sum has occurred, so the initial row, row 2, is [1].
%e A397173 For row 3, we have also W(1)+W(3) = 0+1=1 and W(2)+W(3) = 0+1 = 1, so the sum 0 still occurs once, but now the sum 1 has occurred twice. So the next row is [1,2].
%o A397173 (Python)
%o A397173 from collections import Counter
%o A397173 from itertools import count, islice
%o A397173 def A397173_gen(): # generator of terms
%o A397173     alst, an, c = [], 0, Counter()
%o A397173     for n in count(1):
%o A397173         an = c[an]
%o A397173         c.update(an+ai for ai in alst)
%o A397173         if n >= 2: yield from (c[k] for k in range(max(c.keys())+1))
%o A397173         alst.append(an)
%o A397173 print(list(islice(A397173_gen(), 107))) # _Michael S. Branicky_, Jun 26 2026
